flowRoot.flowPara: The Sol Genomics Network (SGN) is a resource for plant genetic, genomic, and phenotypic information. Our data is centered on the Solanaceae family, but extends to other plants in the Asterid clade.
This brochure introduces SGN and highlights some of the tools and data available.

SGN is the bioinformatics hub for the ongoing Tomato genome sequencing project. Tomato has been sequenced by an international consortium as a high quality reference sequence for the Asterids. A next-generation whole genome shotgun assembly has been generated and assembed. The genome can be browsed using Gbrowse, or analyzed using BLAST among other tools.

The SGN Locus database is a community curated repository of gene information. Each locus can be assigned to a 'locus editor' from the research community, who can edit the locus information.
Loci data includes images, ontology annotations, publications, alleles and sequences, genetic map locations, and user comments.
View and compare genetic maps of tomato, potato, pepper, and other species.
Use these two integrated tools to seamlessly browse phylogenetic trees and multiple alignments. Use either SGN gene families or upload your own data.

The SolCyc collection of pathway databases represents the metabolism of reference species, including tomato, potato, and pepper. Use the Omics viewer to quickly identify biochemical effects by overlaying expression data on SolCyc's curated pathway schemas.
SGN's BLAST tool combines power, speed, and ease of use.

A wide-ranging selection of plant, organelle, and global DNA sets are available for BLAST, including sequences from SGN, TAIR, NCBI, and UniProt/Swiss-Prot, all updated daily or weekly. Up to date data-sets from the tomato genome project are available.

SGN contains a repository for raw quantitative trait loci (QTL) data, coupled with R/QTL mapping software for on-the-fly QTL mapping analysis and visualization, called solQTL.
Using this tool, researchers can calculate and quickly compare QTLs of their interest with other genetic and genomic maps in the database and identify candidate genes.

The SGN phenotype database contains information on plant accessions from mutant and mapping populations as well as collections of varieties, breeder lines, and experimetally designed segregating populations. Each phenotyped line can be traced for crosses and experiments, such as phenotyping and genotyping. All phenotype data and annotations, such as ontologies, publications, and linked loci, are editable in a similar manner to the locus database
